definition: "Phosphorus is the second most abundant mineral in the body after calcium, with approximately 85% stored in bone as hydroxyapatite (calcium phosphate mineral matrix), 14% in soft tissues as organic phosphates (ATP, phospholipids, nucleic acids, phosphoproteins), and less than 1% circulating in blood as inorganic phosphate (Pi). The serum phosphorus test measures this small circulating inorganic phosphate fraction. Phosphorus is ubiquitous in the food supply — found in virtually all protein-containing foods and as an additive (phosphoric acid, phosphate salts) in processed foods, carbonated beverages, and food preservatives. Intestinal phosphorus absorption is efficient and poorly regulated compared to calcium: approximately 60–70% of dietary phosphorus is absorbed without tight hormonal control. Serum phosphorus is regulated primarily by PTH (which reduces renal tubular phosphorus reabsorption, increasing urinary excretion), FGF-23 (fibroblast growth factor 23 — a bone-derived phosphaturic hormone), and active vitamin D (which increases intestinal phosphorus absorption). The kidney is the primary regulator of phosphorus balance through tubular excretion."
why_it_matters: "Phosphorus sits at an unusual position in longevity medicine: it is both essential (required for ATP, bone, and DNA) and potentially harmful in excess. The emerging evidence from epidemiology is striking — multiple large cohort studies in the general population (not just kidney disease patients) have found that serum phosphorus in the high-normal range (3.5–4.5 mg/dL) is independently associated with increased cardiovascular mortality and all-cause mortality. The NHANES III analysis found that phosphorus above 3.5 mg/dL was associated with 35–55% higher cardiovascular mortality risk in adults without kidney disease, after adjustment for traditional risk factors. The proposed mechanisms involve FGF-23 elevation (FGF-23 has direct cardiac hypertrophic effects and promotes vascular calcification), direct vascular smooth muscle calcification in high phosphorus environments, and endothelial dysfunction. The primary dietary driver of high-normal phosphorus in Western populations is the exceptionally high phosphate additive content of processed foods and carbonated beverages — phosphate additives have near-complete absorption compared to the ~60% absorption of organic food phosphorus."

